it nearly didn't make it <i>off</i> the runway.

688
00:49:16,871 --> 00:49:17,913
But you kept busy.

689
00:49:18,080 --> 00:49:23,127
Ferrying out the torture apparatus
of our friend's fallen dictatorship.

690
00:49:23,586 --> 00:49:25,087
It's getting worse.

691
00:49:25,254 --> 00:49:28,215
Everyone who lands at Mehrabad
now fills in one of these.

692
00:49:29,383 --> 00:49:33,262
That slip makes a copy to the one underneath.
Passenger keeps yellow, airport keeps white.

693
00:49:33,429 --> 00:49:34,972
When you leave, they match them up...

694
00:49:35,139 --> 00:49:37,516
...to verify you came into the country
when you say you did.

695
00:49:37,683 --> 00:49:41,645
So if they look, they'll see I didn't come
into the country with six people.

696
00:49:42,396 --> 00:49:44,148
If they look.

697
00:49:46,192 --> 00:49:51,197
When you land, you should go straight to
the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance...

698
00:49:51,405 --> 00:49:52,823
...to kiss the ring.

699
00:49:52,990 --> 00:49:56,202
Get on record as having applied
for a film permit.

700
00:49:56,535 --> 00:50:00,122
If they catch you later, at least they'll be
confused while they're torturing you.

701
00:50:04,084 --> 00:50:08,047
IRANIAN CONSULATE - TURKEY

702
00:50:17,848 --> 00:50:19,975
What will be the purpose
of your visit to Iran?

703
00:50:20,351 --> 00:50:23,479
Uh, film production. Business.

704
00:50:25,856 --> 00:50:28,651
Why didn't you get your visa in Canada?

705
00:50:30,027 --> 00:50:33,864
I would've loved to, except my boss
didn't send a telex till I got here.

706
00:50:34,532 --> 00:50:38,118
Guy had an intelligent thought in his head,
it would die of loneliness.

707
00:50:59,098 --> 00:51:01,809
The <i>Times</i> and AP found out six escaped.

708
00:51:01,976 --> 00:51:05,312
They know who they are and they know
they're hiding out with the Canadians.

709
00:51:05,479 --> 00:51:07,273
Somebody with one of the families talked.

710
00:51:07,481 --> 00:51:08,816
Mother of God.

711
00:51:08,983 --> 00:51:11,777
Yeah, I just put Vance on a plane
to take the editors to Le Cirque.

712
00:51:11,944 --> 00:51:14,405
He thinks he can
get them to sit on it, for now.

713
00:51:15,406 --> 00:51:17,366
Your guy better get them...

714
00:51:18,033 --> 00:51:19,910
...and get the hell out.

715
00:51:20,703 --> 00:51:23,664
<i>The captain has informed
us that we have entered Iranian airspace.</i>

716
00:51:23,831 --> 00:51:28,335
<i>We'll be coming through to collect
any remaining alcoholic beverages.</i>

717
00:54:06,535 --> 00:54:08,203
This film crew is just yourself?

718
00:54:08,746 --> 00:54:11,707
No, we have six more from Canada
meeting us today.

719
00:54:11,874 --> 00:54:13,709
You like to film at the bazaar?

720
00:54:14,209 --> 00:54:16,044
The bazaar, maybe the palace.

721
00:54:16,879 --> 00:54:18,505
Landmark sites.

722
00:54:18,714 --> 00:54:20,299
I see.

723
00:54:21,091 --> 00:54:22,968
The exotic Orient.

724
00:54:23,385 --> 00:54:26,764
Snake charmers, flying carpets.

725
00:54:27,681 --> 00:54:30,559
You came to us at a complicated time.

726
00:54:30,726 --> 00:54:34,730
Before the revolution, 40 percent of the movie
theaters in Tehran were showing pornography.

727
00:54:35,898 --> 00:54:37,149
I understand.

728
00:54:37,316 --> 00:54:40,486
The function of this office is purification...

729
00:54:40,694 --> 00:54:43,947
...as well as promotion for the arts.

730
00:54:45,240 --> 00:54:47,826
I'll review this for the minister.

731
00:54:48,577 --> 00:54:49,995
Okay. Thank you.

732
00:54:58,420 --> 00:55:01,215
Lester, you're working late.

733
00:55:01,381 --> 00:55:03,300
Till the dawn's early light.

734
00:55:03,467 --> 00:55:07,346
You got stamina, Lester. I wanna be you.

735
00:55:07,554 --> 00:55:10,390
Well, I'm 150 years old,
so you wouldn't be me for long.

736
00:55:20,317 --> 00:55:22,486
- Mr. Ambassador.
- Ken Taylor.

737
00:55:22,653 --> 00:55:24,154
Thank you for what you're doing.

738
00:55:24,947 --> 00:55:27,783
I was expecting more of a G-man look.

739
00:55:28,867 --> 00:55:30,869
I think you're thinking of the FBI, sir.

740
00:55:31,662 --> 00:55:33,997
Ah. This way.

741
00:55:46,134 --> 00:55:49,847
- These are blank, you know. Stamps...
- Yeah, I'll take care of this.

742
00:55:52,057 --> 00:55:53,183
How long?

743
00:55:53,392 --> 00:55:56,186
A day, prep their covers.
Two if they need it.

744
00:55:56,353 --> 00:55:57,688
And you'll fly out with them?

745
00:55:58,105 --> 00:55:59,731
Yeah.

746
00:55:59,898 --> 00:56:01,567
There's something you should know.

747
00:56:01,775 --> 00:56:05,028
We think our housekeeper
has figured out who they are.

748
00:56:05,571 --> 00:56:10,033
We don't know if we can trust her,
so sooner is better.

749
00:56:59,917 --> 00:57:01,209
Hi.

750
00:57:01,376 --> 00:57:03,253
My name's Kevin Harkins...

751
00:57:04,338 --> 00:57:05,923
...and I'm gonna get you home.

752
00:57:07,382 --> 00:57:10,010
These are the screenplays
for your cover identities.

753
00:57:11,637 --> 00:57:14,097
It's theater of the absurd.

754
00:57:14,264 --> 00:57:16,850
- What are our chances?
- Your chances are good.

755
00:57:17,017 --> 00:57:20,145
"Good"? Well, what's the number value
of "good"?

756
00:57:20,354 --> 00:57:23,065
Thirty percent chance
of being publicly executed?

757
00:57:23,231 --> 00:57:26,777
Can you tell me what the objection was
to normal cover identities?

758
00:57:26,944 --> 00:57:29,154
There are no Canadians in the country
for normal reasons.

759
00:57:29,321 --> 00:57:30,864
- They'll sniff us out regardless.
- The Swedish Consul?

760
00:57:31,031 --> 00:57:34,701
They accused him of being an American
at the airport. They held him for an hour.

761
00:57:34,868 --> 00:57:37,913
We can't hold up under that.
We don't know what the hell movie people do.

762
00:57:38,080 --> 00:57:39,206
That's why I'm here.

763
00:57:39,373 --> 00:57:42,876
I'm gonna help you. I'll be with you
the whole way. This is what I do.

764
00:57:43,043 --> 00:57:45,087
Have you gotten people out
this way before?

765
00:57:46,421 --> 00:57:47,923
This would be a first.

766
00:57:49,424 --> 00:57:53,011
Do you know that every day they catch
another friend of the shah at the airport?

767
00:57:53,178 --> 00:57:55,681
Kangaroo trials and then firing squads...

768
00:57:55,889 --> 00:57:58,600
...just for having American names
in their phone books.

769
00:57:58,767 --> 00:58:00,227
You've been here an hour.

770
00:58:00,394 --> 00:58:02,813
And you're asking us to trust you
with our lives, Mr...?

771
00:58:02,980 --> 00:58:04,314
Harkins.

772
00:58:04,523 --> 00:58:06,316
That's your real name?

773
00:58:06,984 --> 00:58:08,151
No.

774
00:58:11,113 --> 00:58:14,908
I know there are risks involved.
Serious risks.

775
00:58:15,409 --> 00:58:17,119
But it is time to go.

776
00:58:19,579 --> 00:58:23,208
We've got orders to close the embassy
and go back. There's nowhere for them to stay.

777
00:58:25,711 --> 00:58:29,423
We will never make it through
immigration at the airport. I'm serious.

778
00:58:29,589 --> 00:58:33,510
No, no, no, this is what, the part when
we say this is so crazy it might actually work?

779
00:58:33,677 --> 00:58:35,512
Joe, I saw it in Burma. They get people out.

780
00:58:35,679 --> 00:58:38,932
Snitches in banana republics?
They get them over the border after the coup.

781
00:58:39,099 --> 00:58:40,142
That's your opinion, Joe.

782
00:58:40,308 --> 00:58:42,477
You know, his opinion got us out
in the first place.

783
00:58:42,978 --> 00:58:47,107
If we go out there with fake passports,
we are spies, period. That's execution.

784
00:58:47,274 --> 00:58:49,818
- You got a problem lying, Joe?
- Point is, we can't stay here.

785
00:58:50,485 --> 00:58:54,114
If we get caught, you and Pat go on trial
for harboring the enemy, you know that?

786
00:58:54,281 --> 00:58:56,867
Pat and I have discussed it.
It's the risk we took.

787
00:58:57,659 --> 00:59:00,579
That man out there
has got bad cards and he is going to lose.

788
00:59:00,746 --> 00:59:04,041
And if he loses, it's our lives.

789
00:59:05,333 --> 00:59:07,335
And his life too.

790
00:59:08,754 --> 00:59:10,672
Look, we don't have any alternatives.

791
00:59:10,839 --> 00:59:12,049
We gotta go.

792
00:59:18,555 --> 00:59:22,017
These cover identities were created
specifically for each one of you.

793
00:59:22,184 --> 00:59:24,728
What you need to do is memorize
everything that's inside.

794
00:59:24,895 --> 00:59:27,814
Who you are, what you are,
where you've been. Complete bio.

795
00:59:27,981 --> 00:59:29,066
And then add to that.

796
00:59:29,232 --> 00:59:32,652
Where do you vacation? What are your
allergies? Who'd you have an affair with?

797
00:59:32,819 --> 00:59:33,987
The only way this works...

798
00:59:34,154 --> 00:59:37,824
...is if you believe that you're these people
so much that you dream like them.

799
00:59:38,784 --> 00:59:40,494
Get started tonight.

800
00:59:41,203 --> 00:59:44,206
I'll be back tomorrow.
We'll get going. Good luck.

801
00:59:49,795 --> 00:59:51,505
Well, my guy kind of sucks.

802
00:59:51,671 --> 00:59:53,048
What's your name?

803
00:59:53,757 --> 00:59:56,051
Mike McEwan, eh? Heh.

804
00:59:57,010 --> 00:59:58,053
That was convincing.

805
00:59:58,220 --> 00:59:59,888
Kathy, what's your name?

806
01:00:27,874 --> 01:00:31,086
The Love Boat
<i>will be seen 15 minutes from now.</i>

807
01:00:31,253 --> 01:00:35,048
<i>The State Department insisted today
that the crisis in Afghanistan...</i>

808
01:00:35,215 --> 01:00:39,302
<i>...will not divert the attention of the
United States from the plight of the hostages.</i>

809
01:00:39,469 --> 01:00:42,180
<i>--Is perceived to be if not impotent,
then at least reluctant...</i>

810
01:00:42,347 --> 01:00:46,852
<i>Now the United States finds itself in such
bitter confrontation with the Soviet Union...</i>

811
01:00:47,018 --> 01:00:49,855
<i>...over that country's invasion
of Afghanistan...</i>

812
01:00:50,063 --> 01:00:52,482
<i>The United States
is now moving toward a decision...</i>

813
01:00:52,649 --> 01:00:54,693
<i>...to boycott the Summer Olympics
in Moscow...</i>

814
01:00:55,861 --> 01:00:59,072
Bad news, bad news.
Even when it's good news, it's bad news.

815
01:00:59,447 --> 01:01:03,577
John Wayne's in the ground six months,
this is what's left of America.

816
01:01:32,105 --> 01:01:35,734
<i>"The Minister of Culture and Guidance
has approved your location scout.</i>

817
01:01:35,901 --> 01:01:37,819
He will send his representative to meet
you and your crew...

818
01:01:37,986 --> 01:01:41,573
...at the Khayyam entrance
to the Grand Bazaar tomorrow at 3 p.m."

819
01:01:42,449 --> 01:01:43,617
They called your bluff.

820
01:01:43,783 --> 01:01:46,369
- Maybe they're cooperating.
- <i>Absolutely not.</i>

821
01:01:46,786 --> 01:01:51,166
Seven Americans walking the bazaar
is asking for a riot. It's the hive.

822
01:01:51,333 --> 01:01:52,667
Seven Canadians, Jack.

823
01:01:52,834 --> 01:01:55,962
<i>Never give them multiple shots at a cover.</i>

824
01:01:56,671 --> 01:01:57,964
Are they even ready?

825
01:01:58,131 --> 01:01:59,382
They're getting there.

826
01:01:59,549 --> 01:02:01,092
There's no prize for "Most Improved."

827
01:02:01,259 --> 01:02:03,970
I don't have a choice.
We say no, they show up at the residence...

828
01:02:04,137 --> 01:02:06,765
...and drag everyone out.
You think their covers are gonna hold up...

829
01:02:06,932 --> 01:02:08,767
...when they're getting their fingernails
pulled out?

830
01:02:29,537 --> 01:02:32,791
You want us to go to the Grand Bazaar
at 3:00 in the afternoon?

831
01:02:33,875 --> 01:02:36,878
You said a day to learn our covers,
then straight to the airport.

832
01:02:37,045 --> 01:02:38,672
They suspect something?

833
01:02:38,838 --> 01:02:41,591
What I know is,
we need to pretend to be a movie crew.

834
01:02:41,758 --> 01:02:45,178
We go to the bazaar today,
we fly out from the airport tomorrow.

835
01:02:47,264 --> 01:02:48,682
We won't do it.

836
01:02:50,475 --> 01:02:53,186
He told them that there were six of us.
So they're expecting six.

837
01:02:53,353 --> 01:02:55,563
It would be suspicious
not to show up at this point.

838
01:02:55,730 --> 01:02:57,857
What else do we have to do, all right?

839
01:02:58,024 --> 01:03:00,568
He's about to show them
the only cards that we're holding...

840
01:03:00,735 --> 01:03:04,406
- ...which is that they don't know we're here!
- That's the ball game, okay?

841
01:03:04,572 --> 01:03:06,700
Look, we don't have any other choice!

842
01:03:06,866 --> 01:03:09,202
Who says that we'll know our covers
well enough?

843
01:03:09,369 --> 01:03:11,121
We're not in the CIA.

844
01:03:12,247 --> 01:03:13,873
It's suicide.

845
01:03:14,040 --> 01:03:16,126
I'm asking you to trust me.

846
01:03:17,544 --> 01:03:18,712
I don't trust you.

847
01:03:21,256 --> 01:03:23,800
This is the game, Joe.
What world are you living in?

848
01:03:23,967 --> 01:03:27,595
The one where they're hanging people
from construction cranes, Bob.

849
01:03:28,388 --> 01:03:30,849
It's too dangerous.
I won't bring my wife into the bazaar.

850
01:03:32,934 --> 01:03:34,269
Joe?

851
01:03:40,984 --> 01:03:42,819
So we'll see you at 2.

852
01:04:05,675 --> 01:04:10,764
So don't be recognizable
but look exactly like your passport photo.

853
01:04:12,015 --> 01:04:14,476
I haven't been this nervous
since our wedding.

854
01:04:16,269 --> 01:04:18,355
Only this isn't a huge mistake, hopefully.

855
01:04:19,814 --> 01:04:21,691
Sorry. Okay.

856
01:04:24,444 --> 01:04:25,779
Hello?

857
01:04:28,531 --> 01:04:29,949
Hello?

858
01:04:30,658 --> 01:04:31,785
Hello?

859
01:04:38,666 --> 01:04:39,959
Who was that?

860
01:04:43,296 --> 01:04:45,006
- Mark?
- Yeah?

861
01:04:47,300 --> 01:04:48,885
I'm scared.

862
01:04:51,221 --> 01:04:52,472
It's okay.

863
01:05:40,353 --> 01:05:41,521
Where are they?

864
01:05:41,688 --> 01:05:43,022
In the kitchen.

865
01:05:59,956 --> 01:06:03,418
This is what I do. I get people out.

866
01:06:04,919 --> 01:06:07,755
And I've never left anyone behind.

867
01:06:09,466 --> 01:06:11,801
I wish I could believe you, Mr. Harkins.

868
01:06:16,931 --> 01:06:20,226
My name is Tony Mendez.
I'm from New York.

869
01:06:20,393 --> 01:06:23,146
My father worked construction.
My mother teaches elementary school.

870
01:06:23,313 --> 01:06:25,690
I have a wife and a 10-year-old son.

871
01:06:28,109 --> 01:06:32,780
You play along with me today,
I promise you, I will get you out tomorrow.

872
01:06:37,160 --> 01:06:38,870
Fuck.

873
01:07:19,452 --> 01:07:21,329
Shit.

874
01:07:48,356 --> 01:07:49,857
Hang on.

875
01:08:38,031 --> 01:08:39,657
You all right?

876
01:08:44,912 --> 01:08:47,081
Okay. Tell me who you are.

877
01:08:47,790 --> 01:08:50,043
Mike McEwan, cameraman.

878
01:08:50,585 --> 01:08:52,795
Robert Baker, director.

879
01:08:53,254 --> 01:08:55,256
Timothy Harris, location manager.

880
01:08:55,423 --> 01:08:57,425
Mary Ann Boyd, screenwriter.

881
01:08:57,592 --> 01:08:59,344
Rachel Dewart, production designer.

882
01:08:59,552 --> 01:09:01,262
Sean Bissett, associate producer.

883
01:09:01,429 --> 01:09:03,973
All right. Let's go make a movie.

884
01:09:17,278 --> 01:09:19,280
Welcome, welcome.
My name is Reza Bolhani.

885
01:09:19,447 --> 01:09:21,824
- Kevin Harkins. I'm the producer.
- Nice to meet you.

886
01:09:21,991 --> 01:09:23,618
This is Mike McEwan, our cameraman.

887
01:09:23,785 --> 01:09:25,995
This is Tim.
This is Mary, our screenwriter.

888
01:09:26,162 --> 01:09:27,664
And this is our director, Bob Baker.

889
01:09:27,830 --> 01:09:29,582
- You are the director?
- Yes.

890
01:09:29,749 --> 01:09:32,210
Is this film a foreign-bride film?

891
01:09:33,127 --> 01:09:34,420
Sorry?

892
01:09:34,587 --> 01:09:37,048
A film where a foreign bride comes to Iran...

893
01:09:37,215 --> 01:09:40,760
...but she doesn't understand the language
or the customs...

894
01:09:40,927 --> 01:09:43,471
...and there is misunderstandings
and laughs.

895
01:09:43,638 --> 01:09:45,098
Oh, no.

896
01:09:50,311 --> 01:09:55,775
The bazaar in Tehran
is one of the largest in the world.

897
01:09:56,359 --> 01:10:00,530
This bazaar has been on this spot
for over 8000 years.

898
01:10:00,697 --> 01:10:04,909
You can find many items
such as paper, spices...

899
01:10:05,118 --> 01:10:07,620
...precious metals, all right here.

900
01:10:07,787 --> 01:10:08,996
Right this way, please.

901
01:10:14,377 --> 01:10:15,753
This way.

902
01:10:30,852 --> 01:10:32,145
- Uh, Mike?
- Yeah.

903
01:10:32,311 --> 01:10:36,482
If I was to say you're looking through the
wrong end of that viewfinder, would I be right?

904
01:10:38,776 --> 01:10:40,361
Yup.

905
01:10:47,577 --> 01:10:48,703
Just a little further.

906
01:11:18,691 --> 01:11:21,944
Please wait here. Let's stay together.

907
01:11:38,753 --> 01:11:40,505
He wants the photograph you took.

908
01:11:40,671 --> 01:11:43,758
It's okay, it's her job to take photographs.
She's the production designer.

909
01:11:43,925 --> 01:11:47,178
He says he did not give you permission
to take a photograph of his store.

910
01:11:47,345 --> 01:11:50,014
That's okay. You can tell him he can have it.

911
01:11:51,307 --> 01:11:53,392
Please, please, just take the photograph.

912
01:12:03,194 --> 01:12:04,237
Peace be upon you.

913
01:12:04,403 --> 01:12:05,780
And upon you, sir. Welcome.

914
01:12:05,947 --> 01:12:07,198
I hope you are well.

915
01:12:07,365 --> 01:12:09,033
Thank you very much. How are you?

916
01:12:09,242 --> 01:12:11,619
I'm very well. What's your name?

917
01:12:11,786 --> 01:12:12,954
Sahar.

918
01:12:23,965 --> 01:12:27,134
He's saying that the shah killed his son
with an American gun.

919
01:12:36,811 --> 01:12:39,188
No, no, no! No! Canada!

920
01:12:39,355 --> 01:12:40,398
Canada!

921
01:12:40,565 --> 01:12:42,859
I would like to suggest that we end our visit.

922
01:12:52,201 --> 01:12:53,286
You know, sister...

923
01:12:53,452 --> 01:12:57,456
...those who are with him, Rasool of Allah,
we are tender among ourselves.

924
01:12:57,623 --> 01:12:59,166
But stern against the Kufar.

925
01:12:59,792 --> 01:13:01,210
